  "report": {
    "narrative": [
      "Scheduler pressure in the 2026-03-01..2026-03-24 window is concentrated in two partitions: mi3001x and mi2104x. mi3001x shows the highest pending backlog (36 jobs) with high CPU saturation (0.75), while mi2104x has the second-highest pending backlog (26) with moderate CPU saturation (~0.62). In contrast, several other GPU-family partitions (mi3008x, mi3258x, mi3508x) are fully CPU-saturated (1.0) yet show very low pending counts (1–2), indicating that they are busy but not accumulating a visible queue at the evaluation time.\n\nWhich GPU families are saturated:\n- Fully saturated (CPU saturation = 1.0): mi3008x, mi3258x, mi3508x. This suggests these partitions are running at capacity (at least on CPU allocation/consumption), even if they are not currently showing large pending queues.\n- High but not full: mi3001x (0.75), mi2508x (0.7), staff (~0.656), mi2104x (~0.619).\n- Low: devel (0.25).\n\nWhere pending jobs are concentrated:\n- mi3001x: 36 pending (largest single source of queueing pressure).\n- mi2104x: 26 pending (second-largest backlog).\n- All others are minor at this snapshot: mi3008x (2), mi3258x (2), and 1 each in mi2508x, mi2101x, mi3508x, devel.\n\nImplications (capacity bottlenecks vs scheduling imbalance):\n- Primary bottleneck appears to be capacity/availability in mi3001x and mi2104x specifically (strong demand relative to supply), not a uniform cluster-wide queue. These partitions likely represent the most in-demand GPU families (e.g., MI300 1x nodes and MI210 4x nodes) where users are targeting a specific accelerator topology.\n- The presence of full saturation without large pending queues (mi3008x/mi3258x/mi3508x) is consistent with steady-state full utilization where demand is being met quickly or where job submission rate is lower; it can also indicate policy effects (limits/priority) preventing queue buildup even though resources are fully utilized.\n- Potential scheduling imbalance hypothesis (weaker evidence): if mi3008x/mi3258x/mi3508x are compatible substitutes for mi3001x workloads, the large mi3001x queue could reflect constraints like job feature requests, GPU count/topology requirements, memory needs, or partition access controls—rather than absolute cluster scarcity. Confirming this requires job constraint/feature data and GRES requests (not included in the preview).\n\nConfidence: high on the queue concentration and saturation values reported; medium on interpreting “GPU family saturation” because the saturation metric shown is CPU saturation per partition (not direct GPU saturation), and no running-vs-idle GPU allocation metrics are included in this preview."
    ],
